@Mean Old Lady

I used to work for L'Oreal, in a warehouse that had customer service and management upstairs and the "floor" (where packing orders and returns took place) downstairs. The cafeteria was also downstairs. The brands in the building were varied, and included fragrances. One man, who was on the, ahem, large side, bathed in a particular scent that was probably only still on the market because he personally bought every conceivable version of it. And he joined our table for lunch. I could not sit near him. You could smell him coming. Complaints were made (separately, by at least 8 people) to HR, who did speak to him, but nothing changed. 

Finally, I said to him directly, "I'm sorry, Jack, but as much as I enjoy your conversation, I cannot bear the (name of fragrance); it literally makes me ill." And I picked up my tray and moved to another table. Eventually the other ladies at our table followed me. He finally toned it down. I felt terrible about doing that, but it was so awful, and made my food taste awful as well. But it worked. I agree with you; it was just as bad or worse than the cigarette smoke. And I hate cigarette smoke!

@Mean Old Lady
Oh yes, the cigarette smoke. The pubs I ran used to stink of that and stale alcohol in the mornings. Disgusting. The only place worse was an office in Milan I worked in for a period; unfiltered smokes and extra strong Italian coffee every morning. As someone who’s never smoked and never drank the black tar they called coffee it was vile. 
But. Italian men do know how to dress and generally smelled divine. Small recompense.

@Bruce

I have no idea how many sq ft the building is, but it housed active cosmetics (where I worked), fragrances, ecomm, major fashion lines, and more. 

I loved working there; they were really good to us. I left when my husband's job moved us to Milwaukee, and shortly after I left, a major cut and shift in personnel happened, so it was probably good timing. But as far as employers go, they were among the best.

